No, JSR-330 does not have the equivalent of Spring&#39;s `@Bean` or Guice&#39;s `@Provides` annotations.

There are only 5 annotations in JSR-330, and they are equivalent to the following Spring&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; / Guice&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; annotations:

```lang-none
JSR-330      Spring                Guice
----------   -------------------   ------------------
@Inject      @Autowired            @Inject
@Named       @Component            @Named
@Qualifier   @Qualifier            @BindingAnnotation
@Scope       @Scope                @ScopeAnnotation
@Singleton   @Scope(&quot;singleton&quot;)   @Singleton
-            @Scope(&quot;prototype&quot;)   -
```

&lt;sup&gt;*1) From [Using JSR 330 Standard Annotations][1] and [Using JSR 330 Standard Annotations][2]*&lt;/sup&gt;  
&lt;sup&gt;*2) From [JSR-330 Integration][3]*&lt;/sup&gt;

They do not match up exactly, so read the articles listed in the footnotes for full detail.


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/5.2.7.RELEASE/spring-framework-reference/core.html#beans-standard-annotations
  [2]: http://springtechnotes.blogspot.com/2015/12/using-jsr-330-standard-annotations.html
  [3]: https://github.com/google/guice/wiki/JSR330#jsr-330-integration

